I created an interface which allows a Swing Application to invoke a SWT Browser window by clicking some command buttons.  By clicking the buttons, the code will set the Browser URL, and the browser will display the URL.  What's happened when the browser is given a new URL:
                urlField.setText(url);
		browser.setUrl(url);
		browser.setFocus();
		browser.getShell().setActive();

If the browser does not exist, clicking the button will invoke a new browser (shell). The browser will stay for all the subsequent clicks (just that it will display different URLs for different buttons).

The problem is that the browser will just come on top of the Swing application for the first two button clicks.  After that, the browser will display the URL, but it will not be active, and won't come on top.

This happens in both linux and Windows XP.  For linux, it only works for the first click.

You should call

   browser.getShell().forceActive();

instead. Shell.setActive() will only bring the shell to front if another shell in the same display is active. The AWT shell (frame) does not belong to the display even though it is in the same process.

These is the snippet I used to test it:

import java.awt.event.*;
import java.awt.event.WindowEvent;

import javax.swing.*;

import org.eclipse.swt.*;
import org.eclipse.swt.browser.*;
import org.eclipse.swt.layout.*;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.*;


public class PR164518 {
	static Display display;

static class BrowserManager {

	Shell shell;
	Text urlField;
	Browser browser;

	static BrowserManager instance;

	public synchronized static BrowserManager getInstance() {
		if (instance == null) instance = new BrowserManager();
		return instance;
	}

	public void launchAsWindow() {
		if (shell != null) return;
		display.syncExec(new Runnable() {
			public void run() {
				shell = new Shell(display);
				urlField = new Text(shell, SWT.SINGLE | SWT.BORDER);
				browser = new Browser(shell, SWT.NONE);
				GridLayout layout = new GridLayout();
				shell.setLayout(layout);
				GridData data;
				data = new GridData(GridData.FILL_BOTH);
				browser.setLayoutData(data);
				data = new GridData(GridData.FILL_HORIZONTAL);
				urlField.setLayoutData(data);
				shell.open();
			}
		});		
	}

	public void setBrowserURL(final String url) {
		display.syncExec(new Runnable() {
			public void run() {
				urlField.setText(url);
		        browser.setUrl(url);
		        browser.setFocus();
//		        browser.getShell().forceActive();
		        browser.getShell().setActive();
			}
		});
	}
}

public static void main(String[] args) { 
	display = new Display();
    JFrame frame = new JFrame(); 
    JButton aButton = new JButton("Google"); 
    aButton.addActionListener(new ActionListener() { 
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) { 
                    BrowserManager bm = BrowserManager.getInstance(); 
                    bm.launchAsWindow(); 
                    bm.setBrowserURL("http://www.google.com"); 
            } 
    }); 
    frame.addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
    	public void windowClosing(WindowEvent arg0) {
    		display.asyncExec(new Runnable() {
    			public void run() {
    				display.dispose();
    			}
    		});
    	}
    });
    frame.getContentPane().add(aButton); 
    frame.pack(); 
    frame.show();
    while (!display.isDisposed()) {
    	if (!display.readAndDispatch()) display.sleep();
    }
    System.exit(0);
}
}

The problem was how I determined the servername in the earlier build pages

$servername = $HTTP_SERVER_VARS["SERVER_NAME"];

versus the new

$servername = $_SERVER["SERVER_NAME"];

Seems to work now.

In the previous content assist functionality, an ICompletionListener could be specified to listen to the following events:
public void assistSessionEnded(ContentAssistEvent event) public void assistSessionStarted(ContentAssistEvent event)
The equivalent listener, IContentProposalListener, does not listen to those two events.
PDE needs to know when an assist session is ended in order to reset the state it maintains for custom filtering of java type results.
The current event does not handle the case where the user ends the content assist without selecting a proposal:
public void proposalAccepted(IContentProposal proposal);

talked to Mike - events are needed for the proposal popup opening and closing.

Added API
public interface IContentProposalListener2 {
	public void proposalPopupOpened(ContentProposalAdapter adapter);
	public void proposalPopupClosed(ContentProposalAdapter adapter);
}
and associated add/remove listener API's on ContentProposalAdapter.

Released to HEAD >20061115.
Mike, please try these out and let me know if anything else is needed.

cc'ing Kevin, fyi only.

When Ctrl+Space is initially entered in the text field augmented for field assist, two calls to the following method from IContentProposalProvider are made instead of one:
public IContentProposal[] getProposals(String contents, int position);
In PDE, the first call to getProposals is the most expensive; since, the search scope is the highest and no filtering is available yet. As a result, the second call is undesirable performance-wise from the PDE perspective.

